docs.abstract: Wall Street seems to have decided that the companies will prevail in their antitrust fight with the Justice Department. That’s no sure thing.

docs.abstract: 21st Century Fox and Disney shareholders are scheduled to vote on the proposed deal simultaneously on July 10. The new timeline puts pressure on Comcast, which is considering an all-cash bid for the Fox assets.

docs.abstract: The tech industry is fighting a pending measure that’s even stricter than the recently enacted G.D.P.R. It’s called the ePrivacy Regulation.

docs.abstract: The maker of Huggies and Kleenex will lay off as much as 13 percent of its staff in an effort to reduce costs.
docs.snippet: The maker of Huggies and Kleenex will lay off as much as 13 percent of its staff in an effort to reduce costs.
docs.lead_paragraph: Kimberly-Clark, the maker of Huggies and Kleenex, is laying off about 13 percent of its work force and shedding factories worldwide, amid declining birthrates that are affecting diaper sales and a retail price war that is weighing on profits.

headline.main: Kimberly-Clark Cutting 5,000 Jobs Amid Pressure on Prices
headline.print_headline: The Maker Of Huggies  Plans to Cut  5,000 Jobs

byline.original: By Michael Corkery and Amie Tsang

docs.abstract: A federal incentive aimed at builders is at the center of a dispute over whether public agencies can use it — and how they can pass it along.
docs.snippet: A federal incentive aimed at builders is at the center of a dispute over whether public agencies can use it — and how they can pass it along.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the past decade, hundreds of public projects have benefited from a federal incentive meant to encourage investments in energy-efficient technology. The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey used it to save $1 million on building One World Trade Center and upgrading bus terminals and airports. In Florida, Miami-Dade County sliced $1.13 million off the price tag of an improved cooling system in its county hall, courthouses and downtown sports arena.

headline.main: Tax Break, or Kickback? Energy Benefit Becomes a Lightning Rod
headline.print_headline: Tax Break or Kickback? Dispute Over Energy Benefit

docs.abstract: Tyler Morse of MCR Development envisions a return to the dawn of the jet age when the TWA Hotel opens in 2019 in the former T.W.A. Flight Center.
docs.snippet: Tyler Morse of MCR Development envisions a return to the dawn of the jet age when the TWA Hotel opens in 2019 in the former T.W.A. Flight Center.
docs.lead_paragraph: Aviation has declined from the days when air travel was considered glamorous and exciting. But Tyler Morse, a hotelier planning the first hotel within walking distance of the terminals at Kennedy International Airport, is enthusiastically embracing that earlier time.

headline.main: Updating the Landmark T.W.A. Terminal at J.F.K., This Time as a Hotel
headline.print_headline: At J.F.K., a Glamorous Return to Yesteryear, 1962 to Be Exact

docs.abstract: The retailer said it would revise how it uses criminal background checks, a step meant to quell complaints that it discriminates against black and Hispanic job applicants.
docs.snippet: The retailer said it would revise how it uses criminal background checks, a step meant to quell complaints that it discriminates against black and Hispanic job applicants.
docs.lead_paragraph: Target agreed on Thursday to revise guidelines for how it screens people seeking jobs at its stores, a step meant to quell complaints that the retailer discriminates against black and Hispanic applicants with criminal records that can include offenses too minor or old to affect their performance as employees.

headline.main: Target Agrees to Review Screening of Job Applicants Amid Claims of Bias
headline.print_headline: Target Agrees to Review Its Screening Of Job Applicants Amid Bias Claims

docs.abstract: The airline has walked back from a plan to replace modest monthly incentives with a chance to win a few large awards.
docs.snippet: The airline has walked back from a plan to replace modest monthly incentives with a chance to win a few large awards.
docs.lead_paragraph: Faced with a backlash from employees, United Airlines said Monday it was “pressing the pause button” on a plan to replace its modest monthly bonuses with a lottery system that would have offered large rewards to a few workers at random.

headline.main: United Airlines Pauses Lottery for Bonuses After Employees Rebel Online
headline.print_headline: United Rethinks Plan to Replace Workers’ Bonuses With a Big-Prize Lottery
